      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "4a7b135f3c083715",
        "text": "If you remember that the concept of system is defined by a difference from the environment, by operational closure, that is, by indifference to the environment, then system rationality means undoing that, undoing indifference, indifference - what happens in the environment doesn't happen to us - and reinforcing irritability, sensitivity or resonance, whatever those terms are, in the system. This is a paradoxical or, if you will, utopian movement that means excluding the environment and including it again. If you think of this against the background of a sum-constancy premise, it would be a nonsensical maneuver, a back and forth with no effect, but if you think of complexity as an incremental variable - and this is precisely why I am combining the rationality discussion and the complexity discussion - then you can imagine that a system with, let's say, tested rationality and tested complexity operates differently and is organized differently than simpler systems that do not have this evolution or this planning behind them. That is, one can imagine that among the complexity patterns-you remember that these are always selection patterns-there are those that are better suited to making irritations from the environment processable in the system."
